<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
The statement `url = request->post_url;` assigns a new value to the function parameter `url` (declared `const char *url`), thereby modifying the pointer parameter itself. MISRA C 2023 Rule 17.8 prohibits modifying function parameters (the object pointed to may be modified, but the pointer shall not be). This assignment therefore violates Rule 17.8. A compliant fix is to copy the parameter to a local variable (e.g. `const char *served_url = url;`) and assign to/use that local variable instead of modifying the parameter.
</scenario>

<instruction>
Judge whether the report is correct or not.
</instruction>

explanation:
Agent A is correct. MISRA C 2023 Rule 17.8 prohibits modifying function parameters themselves; pointer parameters may be used to modify the object they point to, but the pointer variable passed as a parameter shall not be assigned to. The statement
  url = request->post_url;
assigns a new value to the parameter pointer url (declared const char *url), so it violates Rule 17.8. (Similarly, the code also does method = MHD_HTTP_METHOD_GET;, which is another violation of the same rule.) A compliant fix is to copy the incoming parameters to local variables (for example: const char *served_url = url; const char *served_method = method;) and use/assign those locals instead of modifying the parameters.
